out the foods we buy in the grocery stores. That changed in 2007 when I read The Omnivore's Dilemma by Michael Pollan, which addresses the wide-ranging implications of food production and consumption. I learned about the horrible health, environmental, and social problems that result from eating processed food with ingredients derived from corn and soy. At the time almost all packaged food was made with some by-product of those two crops. 😏

So simply eliminating heavily processed foods and cooking using mostly fresh, sustainably or locally sourced ingredients became my jam. Thank you California for your abundant harvest! This year I even took a stab at growing my own food. You know the basic stuff like tomatoes, peppers, and squash. Even with a low yield (because I’m a total rookie), it turned out to be one gratifying experiences. 🍅🤓

I want to know, what have you read that inspired a switch in your diet? 👇🏻
